ce:section.ce:para:
The antibacterial groups and the added feature of ROS generation by chitosan and HAC-chitosan derived CQDs offer enhanced features in many applications that currently rely on chitosan [71]. Antibacterial effects of chitosan however, are limited by its poor solubility [72] (see also Fig. 5) and become somewhat stronger after carbonization due to the added functionality of ROS production. ROS however, mainly operates by creating cell wall damage (see 
                        Fig. S2
                     ) that does not necessarily lead to cell death [56]. The maintenance of quaternary ammonium groups in CQDs derived from HAC-chitosan however, contributes significantly to bacterial killing. Together with the added feature of ROS generation, this makes HAC-chitosan CQDs highly suitable for use in applications requiring antibacterial activity. Importantly, these antibacterial effects not only relate to planktonic bacteria (Table 2) but also extend to bacteria in a biofilm-mode of growth (Fig. 5) that is generally difficult to penetrate by antimicrobials.
